after releasing version 1 i noticed it would only replace 1 @ so now it replaces all of them

[CODE]public String transform(String s){
	while (s.contains("@")){
		String varString = s.substring((s.indexOf("@"))+1, s.indexOf(" ", (s.indexOf("@"))+1));
		try {
		Class clazz = this.getClass();
		Field theField = clazz.getField(varString);
		if(theField.getType() == java.lang.String.class){
			String someString = (String)theField.get(this);
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		if(theField.getType().getName().equals("int")){
			String someString = Integer.toString((Integer)theField.get(this));
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		if(theField.getType().getName().equals("boolean")){
			String someString = Boolean.toString((Boolean)theField.get(this));
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		}catch (Throwable e) {
            	System.err.println(e);
		printTo("Cmd UH OH");
         	}
	}
	return s;
}[/CODE]

to use simply add this where ever you want the string an example of this would be:
[CODE]sendMessage(transform("Welcome to Runescape @playerName"));[/CODE]



the next part im posting is if you want custom colors for your variables u transformed i wouldnt replace this with the first one id just add it as a second one and rename it

[CODE]public String transformCC(String s,String sc, String ec){
	while (s.contains("@")){
		String varString = s.substring((s.indexOf("@"))+1, s.indexOf(" ", (s.indexOf("@"))+1));
		try {
		Class clazz = this.getClass();
		Field theField = clazz.getField(varString);
		if(theField.getType() == java.lang.String.class){
			String someString = sc+(String)theField.get(this)+ec;
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		if(theField.getType().getName().equals("int")){
			String someString = sc+Integer.toString((Integer)theField.get(this))+ec;
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		if(theField.getType().getName().equals("boolean")){
			String someString = sc+Boolean.toString((Boolean)theField.get(this))+ec;
			s = s.replace("@"+varString, someString);
		}
		}catch (Throwable e) {
            	System.err.println(e);
		printTo("Cmd UH OH");
         	}
	}
	return s;
}[/CODE]

to use simple call it like transform("text here","colortoturnvariablehere","colortoturnbacktohere");

an example:
sendMessage(transform("Welcome to Runescape @playerName","@red@","@blk@"));




